Laboratory experiments have shown that short RNA-like strands can form under carefully controlled conditions, using purified chemicals, selected temperatures, catalytic minerals, and tightly managed reaction environments. However, this is very different from demonstrating that fully functional self-replicating RNA arose spontaneously in uncontrolled natural warm water. The average RNA fragments produced in many origin-of-life experiments are still vastly shorter and chemically simpler than the length and complexity expected for even a hypothetical primitive self-replicating system or proto-cell. If one compares typical experimentally produced strands of perhaps tens of nucleotides to the hundreds or thousands likely required for a minimally functional RNA world system, then the gap in informational and chemical organization is not merely small but potentially one order of magnitude or more — implying that substantially greater environmental control, stabilization, and sequencing precision would still be required beyond what has yet been demonstrated. In other words, the experiments show that some building steps are chemically plausible, but they do not yet demonstrate the spontaneous emergence of a complete living RNA system from haphazard warm water conditions.


